english:
  title: Imperial Edict Conferring the Title of Great Zen Master upon Hongyuan of the Jogye Order
  author: Choe Ja
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I address this edict to Hongyuan. Among men, rank is elevated by title; titles are proclaimed through virtue. Without position and rank, how else could we distinguish the worthy from the foolish? Thus even within the Buddhist order, there exists a hierarchy of monastic titles—an ancient institution indeed. When a bhiksu possesses such virtue as to bring blessing to both heaven and earth, how could I hesitate to bestow upon him an honored title that serves as exemplar in the assembly hall?

    As for his conduct and insight, they rival the praise of sun and moon, the lauding of heaven and earth—beyond the reach of brush and tongue. Though his comings and goings offer much to contemplate, from the perspective of this master, even the smallest matters exceed what those renowned as spiritual companions could ever aspire to witness.

    Early in his path, he ascended the ranks of the Buddha-selecting examination, then renounced the world and withdrew to the mountains. When his eye of the Way at last opened clear, myself and my ministers, hearing of his renown and yearning for his presence, extended invitations through illustrious temples—not once, but thrice. Yet he firmly declined, steadfastly refusing. He would not plant his staff. His body floats like clouds; fame and profit he discards as easily as worn sandals. Unlike those worldly recluses who take the Southern Mountain as their shortcut to escape, the wanderers beyond convention prize lofty aspirations and spit upon princes and kings. Should sovereigns and ministers humbly implore them, offering sincerity to bring welfare to the multitude, they refuse and retreat—fleeing like rabbits, scurrying like rats through mountains and streams, calling this noble conduct. But such seeks only to fish for a name of purity, fearing the allure of chaos and defilement, shrinking from diligent practice, luxuriating in ease. This is the limited good of the Lesser Vehicle, hardly worthy of guidance.

    But this master is otherwise. Though in ordinary times he suddenly forsook the human realm and dwelt in transcendence, when calamity befell our realm, he answered the sovereign's and ministers' earnest plea. Leading two thousand disciples, the dragon and elephant assembly, he came to the capital, presided over the great dharma assembly, sprinkled the waters of the Southern Stream to wash away the Northern Flood's disaster, and spread the dharma milk widely across the Three Lands. This is truly one who treads upon Vairocana's crown above and opens the gateway of Samantabhadra's conduct below. Is not such a person worthy of honor? Is not such virtue great?

    Therefore, my bestowal of title to elevate him and the appellation of 'Great' to name him flows naturally from principle. Embrace my esteem and embody this auspicious mandate. I hereby grant you this certificate of the title Great Zen Master. Receive it with reverence.
  footnotes:
    - Vairocana (毘盧, Pirocana in Korean) refers to the cosmic Buddha; treading upon his crown symbolizes the highest spiritual attainment and transcendent wisdom.
    - Samantabhadra (普賢, Bohyeon in Korean) represents compassionate action and universal virtue; 'opening the gateway' suggests making these virtues manifest in the world.
    - The 'Southern Stream' and 'Northern Flood' likely refer to specific disasters or threats to the realm that the master's spiritual intervention helped alleviate.
    - The 'dragon and elephant assembly' (龍象) is a traditional metaphor for the most capable disciples, the strongest practitioners of Buddhism.
